1455","1401–Male":"1401–Deceased","1359–1397":"1359–1397","1363–1420":"1363–1420","1363":"1363","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","after 1401":"after 1401","1359":"1359","1401":"1401","about 1418":"about 1418","1378":"about 1378","1455":"1455","1377":"1377","1399":"1399","1388":"1388","1465":"1465","Abt 1397":"about 1397","1398":"1398","1420":"1420","1376":"1376","1397":"1397","about 1399":"about 1399","1418":"1418","Rougham, Suffolk, England":"Rougham, Suffolk, England","Hessett, Suffolk, England":"Hessett, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Bramfield, Suffolk, England":"Bramfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bacon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and French: from the Norman French personal name <i>Bacun</i>, derived from the ancient Germanic name <i>Bac(c)o</i>, <i>Bahho</i>, based on the element <i>bag</i> ‘(to) fight, (to) dispute’. The name was relatively common among the Normans in the form <i>Bacus</i>, of which the oblique case was <i>Bacon</i>.","English and French: from Middle English, Old French <i>bacun</i>, <i>bacon</i> ‘bacon’ (a word of ancient Germanic origin, akin to   Back   3), probably a metonymic occupational name for a preparer and seller of cured pork.","History: Gilles Bacon from Normandy, France, is documented in Quebec City, QC, in 1647. — Michael Bacon from England arrived in Dedham, MA, in 1640. Nathanial Bacon, from Stratton, Cornwall, arrived in Barnstaple, MA, in 1639. Another Nathaniel Bacon (1647–76), from Friston Hall, Suffolk, emigrated to VA and settled at Curl's Neck on the James river."],"variants":[{"name":"Bagg","meanings":["English:","from Middle English <i>bagge</i> ‘bag, pack, bundle’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a maker of bags and sacks of various kinds, including wallets and purses. It might also have been used for a beggar, or for one who carried their belongings in a bag.","from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Bago</i> (<i>Bac(c)o</i>, <i>Bahho</i>), from the root <i>bag-</i> ‘to fight’ (see   Bacon   2)."]},{"name":"Back","meanings":["English (Devon, Kent, Sussex, and Norfolk): from the Middle English personal name <i>Bakke</i> (Old English <i>Bacca</i>). It is of uncertain origin, but may have been a byname in the same sense as 3.","English: nickname from Middle English <i>bakke</i> ‘bat’, of uncertain application, perhaps a nickname for a person with poor eyesight, from the expression ‘blind as a bat’.","English: from Middle English <i>bakke</i> ‘back’ (Old English <i>bæc</i>), hence a nickname for someone with a hunched back or some other noticeable peculiarity of the back or spine, or a topographic name for someone who lived on a hill or ridge, or at the rear of a settlement."]}]},{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bavant","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Shrikant, Narayan, Paras, Rakesh, Sapna, Smita.","French and Italian (Piedmont): probably a variant of   Salvant  .","Indian (Maharashtra): from Sanskrit title <i>sāmanta</i> ‘feudatory prince’, a variant of <i>sawant</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Salvant","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Cyrille, Lucien, Michel.","French: variant of <b>Sauvant</b>, from an old vernacular form of the personal name   Sylvain  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":4,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Bacon De Bavant was born about 1378, in Hessett, Suffolk, England, his father, John Bacon IV, was 20 and his mother, Helena Tillot, was 16. He married Isabel Shelton in 1398, in Hessett, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died about 1418, in Hessett, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 42, and was buried in Hessett, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1378–about 1418":"umbes 1378–umbes 1418","1376–Male":"1376–Surnud","1378–1418":"umbes1378–1418","1382–Male":"1382–Surnud","1385–1465":"1385–1465","1388–Male":"1388–Surnud","1377–1401":"1377–